query = query_schema + """
select
    case when los = 1 then '1' else '1+' end los_group
    ,sum(admits) admits
    ,sum(deaths) deaths
    ,sum(deaths) *1.0 / sum(admits) mortality
from (
    select
        ceil(icu_length_of_stay) los
        ,count(*) admits
        ,sum(death) deaths
        ,sum(death) *1.0 / count(*) mortality
    from (
        SELECT 
            subject_id, hadm_id, icustay_id
            ,EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM outtime - intime) /60.0/60.0/24.0 as icu_length_of_stay
        FROM 
            icustays
        ) a
        left join (
        select 
            *
            , case when deathtime is not null then 1 else 0 end death
        from 
            admissions
        ) d on a.hadm_id = d.hadm_id
    where
        floor(icu_length_of_stay) < 30
    group by
        los
    ) b
group by
    los_group
"""

    SELECT 
        subject_id, hadm_id, icustay_id
        ,EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM outtime - intime) /60.0/60.0/24.0 as icu_length_of_stay

    from

Findings:¶

  • Patients can have multiple hospitalization admissions per patient.
    • For inclusion/exclusion (I/E), only the first ICU stay per patient should be analyzed since we want to maintain independent observations.
  • Most admits and many deaths occur with LOS<=1, and may include the whole spectrum of cases from the completely innocuous (as evidenced by the low mortality rate) to the most urgent (with impending death). By limiting the prediction to admits with LOS>1, we may improve the homogeneity of cases by filtering out the lowest and highest urgency cases. This also allows the testing of first-day data to predict subsequent death in day 2 to be more relevant.
    • Mortality also increases after day 2, which affords the opportunity for prediction to provide some value.

Summarize data post exclusions¶

  • Some common exclusions that should be done:
    • Repeat observations, as noted in the previous section
    • Age, patients less than 18 years old
    • Surgical admits, which I am assuming in most cases are more likely to be elective than emergent
    • LOS, LOS<=1 (too short to use the first-day framework), >=30 (too long and probably representative of different kinds of admits), and nulls

query = query_schema + """
with co as (
select 
    icu.subject_id, hadm_id, icustay_id, intime, outtime
    , extract('epoch' from icu.intime - pat.dob) / 60.0 / 60.0 / 24.0 / 365.242 age
    ,EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM outtime - intime) /60.0/60.0/24.0 as icu_length_of_stay
    , rank() over (partition by icu.subject_id order by icu.intime) icustay_id_order
from 
    icustays icu
    inner join patients pat on icu.subject_id = pat.subject_id
)

, serv as (
SELECT icu.hadm_id, icu.icustay_id, curr_service
    , case when curr_service like '%SURG' or curr_service = 'ORTHO' then 1 else 0 end surgical
    , case when curr_service in ('NB', 'NBB') then 1 else 0 end birth
    , case when curr_service in ('OBS', 'DENT', 'PSYCH') then 1 else 0 end minor_rep
    , rank() over (partition by icu.hadm_id order by se.transfertime desc) as rank
FROM 
    icustays icu
    left join services se on icu.hadm_id = se.hadm_id
        and se.transfertime < icu.intime + interval '12' hour
)

, icd as (
select 
    hadm_id
    ,subject_id
    ,max(case when seq_num = 1 then icd9_code else null end) icd1
    ,max(case when seq_num = 2 then icd9_code else null end) icd2
    ,max(case when seq_num = 3 then icd9_code else null end) icd3
    ,max(case when seq_num = 4 then icd9_code else null end) icd4
    ,max(case when seq_num = 5 then icd9_code else null end) icd5
    ,max(case when seq_num = 6 then icd9_code else null end) icd6
from 
    diagnoses_icd
group by
    hadm_id
    ,subject_id

)

, deaths as (
select 
    *
    , case when deathtime is not null then 1 else 0 end death
from admissions
)

select
    co.subject_id, co.hadm_id, co.icustay_id, co.intime
    , co.age, co.icu_length_of_stay los
    , death
    , icd1, icd2, icd3, icd4, icd5, icd6
    , icustay_id_order
    , serv.curr_service
    , case when co.age < 18 then 1 else 0 end exclusion_age
    , case when co.icustay_id_order <> 1 then 1 else 0 end exclusion_first_stay
    , case when serv.surgical = 1 or serv.curr_service is null then 1 else 0 end exclusion_surgical
    , case when serv.birth = 1 or serv.curr_service is null then 1 else 0 end exclusion_birth
    , case when serv.minor_rep = 1 or serv.curr_service is null then 1 else 0 end exclusion_minor_rep
    , case when co.icu_length_of_stay >= 30 or co.icu_length_of_stay <= 1 or co.icu_length_of_stay is null then 1 else 0 end exclusion_los
from 
    co
    left join serv on co.icustay_id = serv.icustay_id and serv.rank = 1
    left join icd on co.hadm_id = icd.hadm_id
    left join deaths d on co.hadm_id = d.hadm_id
"""
df = pd.read_sql_query(query, con)
df.to_csv('alladmits.csv', sep='\t', encoding='utf-8', index=False)

def preprocess(df):
    output = pd.DataFrame(index=df.index)
    
    if 'charttime' in df:
        del df['charttime']
    
    for col, col_data in df.iteritems():
        
        # delete date columns
        #if col_data.dtype == np.datetime64:
        #    df.drop(col, axis=1)

        # if data is non-numeric, replace with...
        if col_data.dtype == object:
            col_data = col_data.replace(['None'], [np.NaN])
        
        # if data is categorical, create dummy variables
        if col_data.dtype == object:
            col_data = pd.get_dummies(col_data, prefix = col)
              
        # collect the revised columns
        output = output.join(col_data)
    
    return output

def aggflatten(df):
    cols = df.columns
    agg_funcs = ['mean', 'min', 'max']

    # group by unique identifiers and aggregate data
    g = df.groupby(['subject_id', 'hadm_id', 'icustay_id']).agg(agg_funcs)
    
    # concatenate variable with aggregation function, remove concatenated identifiers
    new_cols = [x + '_' + y for x in cols for y in agg_funcs]
    new_cols = [x for x in new_cols if not (x.startswith('subject_id') or x.startswith('hadm_id') or x.startswith('icustay_id'))]
    
    # drop old column hierarchy, set concatenated column names
    g.columns = g.columns.droplevel(0)
    g.columns = new_cols
    
    return g.reset_index()

  • Bands is missing the most data. Bands is the count of immature neutrophils in the blood used for diagnosing infections like sepsis. Since sepsis occurs in 5% of primary causes and bands occurs in 15% of admits, I will not drop the columns and fill the missing values with 0 since a higher number means that sepsis is more probable.
  • Albumin, bilirubin, lactate, ptt, pt, and inr are all generally useful markers, so I will keep them and fill missing values with population medians.
  • GCS (Glasgow coma scale) variables will have missing values filled with the max value, which is the best response possible in the direction of lucidity.
  • All other variables will get missing values filled with population medians.

# fill bands columns with 0 
raw['bands_max'].fillna(value=0, inplace=True)
raw['bands_min'].fillna(value=0, inplace=True)

# fill albumin, lactate, bilirubin with pop max/min in the direction of favorable/normal outcomes
raw['albumin_max'].fillna(value=raw.max(), inplace=True)
raw['albumin_min'].fillna(value=raw.max(), inplace=True)
raw['lactate_max'].fillna(value=raw.max(), inplace=True)
raw['lactate_min'].fillna(value=raw.max(), inplace=True)
raw['bilirubin_max'].fillna(value=raw.min(), inplace=True)
raw['bilirubin_min'].fillna(value=raw.min(), inplace=True)

# select GCS-related columns
gcs_cols = [x for x in raw.columns if 'gcs' in x]

# fill GCS columns with the max
raw[gcs_cols].fillna(value=raw.max(), inplace=True)

# fill all other missing values with the median
raw.fillna(value=raw.median(), inplace=True)

# dropping columns that aren't needed anymore

# create specificity scorer
def specificity(y, y_pred):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)
    res = cm[0,0]*1.0 / np.sum(cm[0,:])
    return res  

# create method that will pass a list of classifiers through scoring metrics and yield a results table
def scoremetrics(clfs): 
    
    results_list = [] 
    
    for clf in clfs:
        if str(clf).split('(',1)[0] == 'GradientBoostingClassifier':
            # fit GB with balanced samples
            clf.fit(X_train, y_train, sample_weight=(np.ones(X_train.shape[0]) / X_train.shape[0]))
        else:     
            clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
        
        res = {}
        # extract the model name from the object string
        res['Model'] = str(clf).split('(',1)[0]
        # get parameters from attribute
        res['Parameters'] = clf.get_params()

        # within each classifier, cycle through metric scorers with train and test sets
        for metric in [roc_auc_score, specificity, precision_score, recall_score]:
            metric_name = metric.__name__
            res[metric_name + '_train'] = metric(y_train, clf.predict(X_train))
            res[metric_name + '_test'] = metric(y_test, clf.predict(X_test))

        results_list.append(res)
        results_df = pd.DataFrame(results_list)
        
    return results_df

def cvscore(clf):
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_test, y_test, cv=10, scoring='roc_auc')
    display(scores)
    display("AUROC: %0.2f (+/- %0.2f)" % (scores.mean(), scores.std() * 2))

def cumulativelift(clf): 
    # combine predicted probability with target
    pred = pd.DataFrame(clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1], columns=['propensity'])
    truth = pd.DataFrame(y_test.reset_index(drop=True))
    df = pd.merge(truth, pred, left_index=True, right_index=True)

    # calculate lift per decile of ranked probability
    df.sort(columns='propensity', ascending=False, inplace=True)
    df.reset_index(drop=True)
    df['seq'] = range(1, len(df) + 1)
    df['percentile'] = 100 - np.floor(df['seq'] *100.0 / (df.shape[0])) - 1
    df.ix[df.percentile==-1.0] = 0.0
    
    # probability of correctly discriminating target with random chance
    randomchance = df.death.sum() / df.death.count()

    # calculate cumulative lift by percentile
    g = df.groupby('percentile', as_index=True).agg(OrderedDict([
                ('death',
                OrderedDict([
                            ('deaths', 'sum'),
                            ('obs', 'count')
                        ]))
            ])).reset_index(col_level=1)
    # flatten headers
    g.columns = g.columns.get_level_values(1)
    # calculate cumulative lift
    g.sort(columns='percentile', ascending=False, inplace=True)
    g['cumulativelift'] = (g.deaths.cumsum() / g.obs.cumsum()) / randomchance
    
    return g

def plot_learning_curve(clf, title, X, y, ylim=None, cv=None,
                        n_jobs=1, train_sizes=np.linspace(.1, 1.0, 5)):
    plt.figure()
    plt.title(title)
    if ylim is not None:
        plt.ylim(*ylim)
    plt.xlabel("Training examples")
    plt.ylabel("Score")
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(
        clf, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    plt.grid()

    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,
                     train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,
                     color="r")
    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,
                     test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="g")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r",
             label="Training score")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="g",
             label="Cross-validation score")

    plt.legend(loc="best")
    return plt

# http://www.futurile.net/2016/03/31/colormaps-in-matplotlib/

import matplotlib.cm as cm
import matplotlib.colors as colors
from cycler import cycler
import random

def get_cmap(N):
    ''' Returns a function that maps each index in 0, 1, ...
        N-1 to a distinct RGB color.'''
    color_norm  = colors.Normalize(vmin=0, vmax=N-1)
    #scalar_map = cm.ScalarMappable(norm=color_norm, cmap='hsv')
    scalar_map = cm.ScalarMappable(norm=color_norm, cmap='cool')
    def map_index_to_rgb_color(index):
        return scalar_map.to_rgba(index)
    return map_index_to_rgb_color
